            <p class="prose">Two things are immediately visible in the chart that qualitative narratives about bitcoin tend to miss.</p>

            <p class="prose"><strong>First, tops are getting smaller.</strong> Bitcoin&rsquo;s cyclical peaks have compressed dramatically: 12.1&times; over trend in 2013, 6.4&times; in 2017, 2.8&times; in 2021, and just 1.1&times; in both the March 2024 top and the October 2025 all-time high. (The 12.1&times; in 2013 reflects early bitcoin&rsquo;s pre-institutional regime, when retail-driven overshoots were far more violent than anything since &mdash; and the compression from 12&times; to 1.1&times; <em>is</em> the maturation evidence.) The euphoric overshoots that defined the early asset have faded every cycle. This is the maturation thesis &mdash; institutional capital, regulated ETF flows, roughly 6.4% of supply held in ETPs, treasury allocations at 49+ public companies, 23 nation-state holders &mdash; rendered as a single visual fact: tops aren&rsquo;t what they used to be.</p>

            <p class="prose"><strong>Second, floors have stayed structurally stable.</strong> Across four different cycles spanning a 90&times; range of absolute prices, the cycle bottoms have all registered between 0.41&times; and 0.66&times; trend &mdash; a tight band. The downside reference hasn&rsquo;t moved while the upside has compressed toward it. The within-cycle entry-price spread has gone from 22&times; (2013 top vs. 2015 floor) to 1.7&times; (2024 March top vs. 2024 August dip). Timing matters less now than it used to; the boundaries are tighter on both sides.</p>

            <aside class="bvsm-as-of-callout" aria-label="Current market position">
                <div class="bvsm-as-of-callout-label">As of May 2026</div>
                <p class="bvsm-as-of-callout-body">Bitcoin sits at <strong>0.59&times; Power Law trend</strong> &mdash; roughly 41% below the trend value. This places today inside the historical floor range (0.41&ndash;0.66&times;), squarely in the lower half of the channel.</p>
            </aside>

            <p class="prose">By the framework&rsquo;s own logic, low-channel readings have historically been structurally favorable entry territory: bitcoin&rsquo;s trend-relative discount tends to compress over multi-year horizons (mean reversion plus continued absolute trend growth). The October 2025 all-time high only managed 12% above trend, and bitcoin has spent more &ldquo;distance&rdquo; below trend than above it in this cycle. <em>The relationship inverts when bitcoin trades above trend</em> &mdash; at upper-channel positions the prudent read is the same framework running in the opposite direction.</p>

            <p class="prose">The chart isn&rsquo;t a forecast &mdash; the Power Law is a central-tendency expectation, not a prediction, and the asset can stay below or above trend for extended periods. The point is that you have a structural reference for reading entry quality in real time. The scenarios below stress-test that reference against entries the framework itself would flag as upper-channel: what would have happened if you&rsquo;d actually bought at cyclical tops like these? The answer rhymes across every cycle &mdash; and it isn&rsquo;t what the &ldquo;what if I&rsquo;d bought the top&rdquo; objection assumes.</p>
        </div>


