            <p class="prose">Four of the cyclical tops marked on the &sect;1 chart are reflected in the calculator below as preset entries &mdash; three obvious above-trend overshoots (2013 at 12.1&times; trend, 2017 at 6.4&times;, 2021 at 2.8&times;) plus the most recent local high (2025 ATH at 1.12&times;). The 2024 March top is omitted from the preset row: at 1.14&times; trend it&rsquo;s barely above trend, normal cycle behavior rather than a stress test worth running in isolation. The calculator runs two scenarios per entry: a single <strong>lump sum</strong> held to today, or <strong>weekly DCA</strong> from that day forward. Compare against the same dollar amount or weekly cadence in the S&amp;P 500 (total return, with dividends reinvested) and the NASDAQ-100 (total return). What&rsquo;s being tested is the framework&rsquo;s <em>strict-conservatism</em> claim: even at entries the Power Law would flag as upper-channel &mdash; entries you wouldn&rsquo;t make if you were using the framework &mdash; the horizons that matter still produced wealth.</p>

            <p class="prose">DCA mode smooths the worst-timing risk because most of the dollars get deployed at prices other than the peak. Lump-sum mode shows the rawest version of the stress test: a single buy on the worst day. The verdict text below each result calls out where the page&rsquo;s argument depends on long-enough holding periods &mdash; particularly for the most recent 2025 ATH preset, where the hold has only had a handful of months to play out. The pattern stabilizes at horizons longer than ~3 years, and decisively at horizons longer than ~5; the older the entry, the more the pattern has had time to assert itself.</p>

